00:06:06.220 --> 00:06:09.290
Graphs and networks.

00:06:09.290 --> 00:06:12.850
OK, let me start
with, what's a graph.

00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:18.190
A graph is a bunch
of nodes and some

00:06:18.190 --> 00:06:20.390
or all of the
edges between them.

00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:23.840
Let me take just a particular
example of a graph.

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:26.570
And this of course
you spot in the book.

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:29.070
Oh and everybody
recognized that,

00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:33.050
and it's probably now corrected,
that in the homework where

00:06:33.050 --> 00:06:37.560
it said 3.4 it meant
2.4, of course.

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:41.080
And this is Section 2.4 now.

00:06:41.080 --> 00:06:44.920
Let me draw a different graph.

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:49.080
Maybe it'll have four
nodes, at those four edges,

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:51.300
let me put in a fifth edge.

00:06:51.300 --> 00:06:54.000
OK, that's a graph.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:55.970
It's not a complete
graph because I

00:06:55.970 --> 00:06:58.930
didn't include that extra edge.

00:06:58.930 --> 00:07:03.100
It's not a tree because
there are some loops here.

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:08.750
So complete graphs
are one extreme where

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:12.350
all the edges are in.

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:14.860
A tree is the other
extreme, where you

00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:16.610
have a minimum number of edges.

00:07:16.610 --> 00:07:19.560
It would only take
probably three edges.

00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:22.860
So just while we're
looking at it,

00:07:22.860 --> 00:07:25.490
there are a bunch
of possible trees

00:07:25.490 --> 00:07:28.540
that would be sort
of inside this graph.

00:07:28.540 --> 00:07:33.220
Sub-graphs of this graph, if
I knock out those two edges

00:07:33.220 --> 00:07:36.670
I have a tree, going out.

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:39.120
Or a tree could be like this.

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:41.720
Or a tree could be like this.

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:48.830
Anyway, five edges is in this
graph, six in a complete graph,

00:07:48.830 --> 00:07:51.640
it would be three
edges in a tree.

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:55.270
OK, and the number
of edges is always m.

00:07:55.270 --> 00:07:59.040
So five edges.

00:07:59.040 --> 00:08:04.160
And the number of nodes
is always n, for nodes.

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:07.720
So A will be five by four.

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:10.030
OK.

00:08:10.030 --> 00:08:15.020
And it's called, so we get a
special name in this world,

00:08:15.020 --> 00:08:19.490
it's called the incidence
matrix of the graph.

00:08:19.490 --> 00:08:21.820
The incidence matrix.

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:24.290
Or, of course,
these things come up

00:08:24.290 --> 00:08:26.380
so often they have
other names, too.

00:08:26.380 --> 00:08:32.120
But incidence matrix is
a pretty general name.

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:34.960
OK, I have to number
the nodes just

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:38.610
so we can create the matrix
A. One, two, three, four.

00:08:38.610 --> 00:08:40.180
And I have to number the edges.

00:08:40.180 --> 00:08:42.860
If I don't number them, I
don't know which is which.

00:08:42.860 --> 00:08:48.250
So let me call this edge
one, from one to two,

00:08:48.250 --> 00:08:51.320
and I'll draw an
arrow on the edges.

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:53.890
So from one to
two, maybe this'll

00:08:53.890 --> 00:08:57.020
be edge two, from one to three.

00:08:57.020 --> 00:08:58.590
This'll be edge three.

00:08:58.590 --> 00:09:01.670
Oh no, let me put edge three
there, would be a natural one,

00:09:01.670 --> 00:09:03.640
say from two to three.

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:07.330
And how about edge four
there, from two to four.

00:09:07.330 --> 00:09:11.070
And edge five going
from three to four.

00:09:11.070 --> 00:09:18.450
OK, so now I have numbered,
I've identified the nodes,

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:20.640
and I've identified the edges.

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:23.390
And there were five
edges and four nodes.

00:09:23.390 --> 00:09:25.590
Usually m is bigger than n.

00:09:25.590 --> 00:09:28.590
We're in this--
Except for trees,

00:09:28.590 --> 00:09:34.720
m will be at least
as large as n.

00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:36.630
And I've put arrows
on, so you could

00:09:36.630 --> 00:09:38.370
say it's a directed graph.

00:09:38.370 --> 00:09:40.280
Because I've given a direction.

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:45.020
You'll see that the directions,
those arrow directions, which

00:09:45.020 --> 00:09:51.180
are just to tell me which way
current should count as plus,

00:09:51.180 --> 00:09:54.490
if it's with the arrow, or which
way it should count as minus

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:55.970
if it's against the arrow.

00:09:55.970 --> 00:09:58.600
Of course, current
could go either way.

00:09:58.600 --> 00:10:01.970
It's just, now I have a
convention of which is plus

00:10:01.970 --> 00:10:03.230
and which is minus.

00:10:03.230 --> 00:10:06.745
OK, so now let me tell
you the incidence matrix.

00:10:06.745 --> 00:10:10.700
So everybody can
get it right away,

00:10:10.700 --> 00:10:12.950
how do you create
this incidence matrix?

00:10:12.950 --> 00:10:15.270
A five by four.

00:10:15.270 --> 00:10:18.710
So it's going to have five
rows, one for every edge.

00:10:18.710 --> 00:10:22.670
So what's the row for edge one?

00:10:22.670 --> 00:10:25.320
And it's got four columns,
one for every node.

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:27.710
So these are the nodes.

00:10:27.710 --> 00:10:32.370
Nodes one, two, three, four.

00:10:32.370 --> 00:10:36.750
So there's a column for every
node and a row for every edge.

00:10:36.750 --> 00:10:39.900
OK, edge one.

00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:43.720
This is just going to tell me
everything about the graph.

00:10:43.720 --> 00:10:47.330
So exactly what's in that
picture will be in this matrix.

00:10:47.330 --> 00:10:49.650
If I've erased one,
I could reproduce it

00:10:49.650 --> 00:10:51.170
by knowing the other one.

00:10:51.170 --> 00:10:55.350
OK, edge one goes from
node one to node two.

00:10:55.350 --> 00:10:59.270
So it leaves node one,
I'll put a minus one there.

00:10:59.270 --> 00:11:00.530
In the first column.

00:11:00.530 --> 00:11:05.660
And a plus one in
the second column.

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:09.680
Edge one doesn't touch
nodes three and four.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:11.670
So there you go,
that's edge one.

00:11:11.670 --> 00:11:14.690
Let me do edge two
and then you'll

00:11:14.690 --> 00:11:16.080
be able to fill in the rest.

00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:21.850
So edge two goes from one to
three, minus one, and a one.

00:11:21.850 --> 00:11:27.170
Edge three goes from two to
three, I'll just keep going.

00:11:27.170 --> 00:11:29.980
Minus one and a one.

00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:35.660
Edge four goes from two to four.

00:11:35.660 --> 00:11:43.370
And edge five goes
from three to four.

00:11:43.370 --> 00:11:44.910
OK.

00:11:44.910 --> 00:11:46.060
Simple, right?

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:47.910
Got it.

00:11:47.910 --> 00:11:50.510
That matrix has got all
the information that's

00:11:50.510 --> 00:11:56.700
in my picture, and the matrix--
But the point about matrices

00:11:56.700 --> 00:11:58.360
is, they do something.

00:11:58.360 --> 00:12:02.740
They multiply a vector
u to produce something.

00:12:02.740 --> 00:12:07.890
They have a meaning beyond
just a record of the picture.

00:12:07.890 --> 00:12:09.460
So A is a great thing.

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:11.300
In fact, what does it do?

00:12:11.300 --> 00:12:12.430
Let's see.

00:12:12.430 --> 00:12:15.050
So that's the matrix
A that we work with.

00:12:15.050 --> 00:12:18.930
Oh, first tell me about Au=0.

00:12:18.930 --> 00:12:22.500
Because we brought up
that subject already.

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:26.460
Are those four
columns independent?

00:12:26.460 --> 00:12:29.010
I've got four columns,
they're sitting

00:12:29.010 --> 00:12:31.540
in five-dimensional space,
there's plenty of room

00:12:31.540 --> 00:12:34.100
there for four
independent vectors.

00:12:34.100 --> 00:12:37.530
Are these four columns
independent vectors?

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:38.400
No.

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:39.420
No, they're not.

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:42.780
Because what combination
of them produces the zero

00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:45.100
vector? [1, 1, 1, 1].

00:12:45.100 --> 00:12:49.010
If I take that column plus
that, plus that, plus that,

00:12:49.010 --> 00:12:54.160
I'm multiplying by-- So, A,
I'll just put that up here

00:12:54.160 --> 00:12:56.920
and then I won't have
to write it again.

00:12:56.920 --> 00:13:05.430
A times [1, 1, 1, 1],
is five zeroes.

00:13:05.430 --> 00:13:10.670
So that u, that
particular u, of all ones,

00:13:10.670 --> 00:13:17.260
is, I would say, in the
null space of the matrix.

00:13:17.260 --> 00:13:21.970
The null space is all
the solutions at Au=0.

00:13:21.970 --> 00:13:24.830
In other words, so
these four columns,

00:13:24.830 --> 00:13:26.690
tell me about the
geometry again.

00:13:26.690 --> 00:13:31.300
These four columns, if I take
all their combinations, yeah.

00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:32.320
Think about this.

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:36.020
If I take all four
combinations, all combinations,

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:37.910
any amount of this
column, this column,

00:13:37.910 --> 00:13:40.780
this column, that
fourth column, those

00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:44.430
are all vectors in
five-dimensional space.

00:13:44.430 --> 00:13:47.270
Now, this isn't
essential but it's good.

00:13:47.270 --> 00:13:50.770
Do you have an idea
of what you'd get?

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:55.140
What would you get if you took,
so this, think of four vectors,

00:13:55.140 --> 00:13:57.890
pointing along, take
all their combinations,

00:13:57.890 --> 00:14:00.180
that kind of fills in.

00:14:00.180 --> 00:14:02.540
Whatever fill in may mean.

00:14:02.540 --> 00:14:04.030
And what does it fill in?

00:14:04.030 --> 00:14:06.320
What do I get?

00:14:06.320 --> 00:14:08.620
What's your image?

00:14:08.620 --> 00:14:09.700
Frankly, I don't know.

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:13.990
I can't visualize
five-dimensional space.

00:14:13.990 --> 00:14:14.840
That well.

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:18.060
But still, we can use words.

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:21.290
What do you think?

00:14:21.290 --> 00:14:23.480
You get a something subspace.

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:28.180
You got a something,
you get something flat.

00:14:28.180 --> 00:14:30.110
I don't know if you do.

00:14:30.110 --> 00:14:32.520
It's pretty flat, somehow.

00:14:32.520 --> 00:14:37.200
Like I'm just asking you to
jump up from a case we know.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:41.780
Where we had columns in
three-dimensional space

00:14:41.780 --> 00:14:44.830
and we took a combination
and they gave us a plane.

00:14:44.830 --> 00:14:47.830
Right, when they were dependent?

00:14:47.830 --> 00:14:51.970
Now, how would you
visualize the combinations

00:14:51.970 --> 00:14:53.250
in five-dimensional space?

00:14:53.250 --> 00:14:56.780
Just for the heck of it?

00:14:56.780 --> 00:15:00.250
It's some kind of a
subspace, I would say.

00:15:00.250 --> 00:15:03.600
And what's its dimension, maybe
that's what I want to ask you.

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:04.640
What's the dimension?

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:07.770
Do I get, like, a
four-dimensional subspace

00:15:07.770 --> 00:15:10.950
of five-dimensional space
when I take the combinations

00:15:10.950 --> 00:15:13.800
of these particular four guys?

00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:15.680
Yes or no?

00:15:15.680 --> 00:15:17.880
Do I get a
four-dimensional subspace,

00:15:17.880 --> 00:15:19.730
whatever that may mean?

00:15:19.730 --> 00:15:20.870
No.

00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:22.680
Right answer, I don't.

